segments.text: Those remember the wrecking ball hitting those columns and bouncing.
They had a heck of a time getting them down.
And so that was a real tragedy.
There was, there's a
metal and glass sculpture that's kind of in a little courtyard here between Rutter Auditorium and Rutter Tower.
It's kind of like a tree that's sitting there.
And some of us immediately dubbed that the ghost of Guyon Hall.
And probably nowadays nobody knows that.
And I understand that no one notified the Guyon family that it was going to happen.
And that they learned of the demolition of the structure when they saw a picture in the Waco paper.
And a couple of years later, they made a very meaningful gift to Baylor.
It was just an unfortunate oversight on somebody's part.
Did you see We've Never Been Licked?
Do you remember?
I have no idea how many times.
I definitely saw it in Guyon Hall.
I can remember seeing it once when I was a senior with a couple of juniors having a good time.
When you were an undergraduate and a group of Aggies went to see a movie in Guyon Hall, what went on during the movie?
Oh, just critiquing the movie as you went.
Out loud?
Reviews out loud, responding with great enthusiasm.
The same thing that happened at the Campus Theater while it operated at Northgate.
Watching a movie there, you'd have to go see it again to know what actually happened.
Because you would have people that had already seen the movie six times, and so everything would be anticipated.
And if you hadn't seen it before, well, then you were at a pretty big disadvantage.
Usually humorous.
Let's see.
I suspect among the unforgettable moments was a certain day in November of 1963.
Where were you when you heard the news of what had happened in Dallas?
I was on the first floor of Moore Hall.
Well, we were getting ready.
I was a junior.
We were getting ready to go to the cut area to cut a couple of trees.
And I guess it was the next night, Friday night, that we met in Guyon Hall.
And we were told that we weren't going to have a bonfire.
We sort of voted, but the decision had already been made that there would not be a bonfire.
How did you hear?
that President Kennedy had been assassinated?
Television.
We were in the hall.
Somebody had on a small little black and white TV.
And I can remember seeing Walter Cronkite.
What did you all do or say?
Shock, total shock.
Everything just changed.
You started listening to every word that you could get.
Rumors started immediately about all the potential causes and stuff happening.
I remember watching everything that was on television in great details.
was watching when Oswald was shot, you know, watching live at that time, watched the funeral procession and, you know, very distinctive memory.
Then that, the football game was the next Thursday here.
We were, you know, beyond lousy.
We were one and eight.
In those days you played ten games.
Texas was nine and oh, number one in the country.
And we played with them all the way.
I think the game was stolen from us.
It was like 13 to 15, I believe.
And the fish drill team advisors, we had a 105 howitzer for the first time in cow field firing it at the game.
It was a very overcast day.
Mark Jackson and I got it.
He was the senior.
Of course, we'd been fished together, if you'll remember the older story.
And O.D.
Butler, who was head of animal science,
was also in the reserves and had artillery pieces.
And so he got us this thing.
Denzel Baker and General Rutter both thought that we had all lost our minds, that this was pretty stupid.
So we had in the simple condition of 1963 Kyle Field, they were worried about the sound.
Well, we were in the north end firing south, and it shook the place, and it was very overcast.
And when we fired, they'd have to wait for the kickoff until the smoke lifted.
And we led most of the game.
Texas was moving on the final drive.
I think Brotherton intercepted.
a ball or picked up a fumble, one or the other.
Intercepted.
Intercepted.
Started running.
If he'd have fell, if he'd have just fallen down, we'd have won the game.
But he ran, he fumbled, they got the ball back.
They kept coming down the field, they threw a pass, and a guy named Whittington, by photo account, you know, intercepted the ball.
But the referee was 20 yards upfield and 20 yards to the side.
and happened to have gone to the University of Texas and called him out of bounds.
And then Texas scored.
General Rutter let school out on Monday because of the effort.
And that became a hoped-for tradition.
Now, see, that's the kind of unforgettable moments that I'm really glad to capture in here.
Let's go back to Bonfire.
Can you recall your fish year bonfire activities?
This year, F2 was a stack unit.
We maybe went to the cut area once, but we predominantly did all our work, you know, loading logs and putting them on the stack.
I remember it, but as I mentioned earlier, my official lady was from Louisiana.
The head yell leader was from Louisiana.
And so we were connected to the head yell leader and we were gophers for him running errands because my fish buddy had a car.
And so we were doing squirrely things.
I don't remember working much, except we did work stack some.
And then... Do you remember where the cutting area was?
I have no idea where it was.
But it wasn't very far away then, was it?
No, it wasn't very far.
Five miles or something maybe.
And the stack area was here?
No, Duncan.
It was already at Duncan.
Already at Duncan.
And about when did the cutting begin?
The week before the fox.
Week before.
If you were going to have the fire on Tuesday or Wednesday, the Thanksgiving week, it was the previous week that cut began.
And during the afternoons of that week, just like when we were getting ready to go when Kennedy was killed, juniors and seniors only could go to the cut area and cut a few trees.
Saturday, Sunday, and Monday, there were no classes on Monday.
were bonfire, and then it burnt on Tuesday.
It was not sophisticated.
It was basically the TP type arrangement.
It should have stayed like that.
And do you have any idea where that year's outhouse came from?
Now, I think for a while, they were definitely stolen.
I think it was probably early 80s before the band started constructing an outhouse.
And finally, well, I think it might have been early 70s.
Because in the early 70s, I was the aide to the commanding general of the 420th Engineer Brigade, Joe Hanover.
And he was the district highway engineer.
and there was the practice of taking every sign that had Austin 28 miles or whatever for 100 miles and bringing them and putting them on the bonfire.
Well, they finally got mad and said, at $25 a sign, or who knows what the cost was, that needs to stop.
So shortly thereafter, students agreed to construct the outhouse and to construct signs that said what they wanted.
And the cutting area, did they yet use chainsaws at all?
There were a few chainsaws.
During your student days, do you remember any injuries?
I can remember a broken leg or something like that.
I don't remember any.
That's serious, but I don't remember any other.
How much partying was there in that era?
I don't remember any.
I have no recall of any of that happening.
You mainly were guarding the campus.
See, in those days we guarded every single sully, cow field.
We had campfires all over the campus guarding the fish pond.
So you just had reasons to be up all night for three days.
Do you remember any invaders that attempted to do this?

Usually if they're my senior year I remember because I was in charge of that of security and we chased some kids and the college station police helped us and they were high school kids you know just being crazy but
You would get this rumor that the Texas fraternity was coming and we would stake out the road, Highway 60 coming in and stuff.
I don't know of anything ever happening.
During your student days, were there any Aggie kidnappings of Southwest Conference mascots?
When I was a junior, that was the year they took them all.
The fall of 63.
I had some of those in class.
Do you remember any of the
reports of that?

The one I remember is Bevo because we had a practice where at 10, 30, or 11, we would go to Coach Norton's, which was a coffee shop, and have coffee and maybe some pancakes and then come back and either go to bed or study.
Well, this was a night when I had a test the next morning, and my intention was to stay up all that night, and I had some no-dos.
Well, I made a mistake.
I took the no-dose, and then I took the coffee.
So when we got back to the residence hall, to the dorm, it was Moore Hall again.
We went in the room, and the guys started telling stories, and I talked all night.
And the only reason I stopped is at about 4.30 or 5 o'clock or sometime, they came in and said, Bevo is over in the Duncan area.
You know, let's go.
And we did, and I did not do well on that test.
And am I correct in remembering that there was no injury damage to Bevo in any way?
And is that the year that when they rented the trailer, they signed their... Oh, that's later when they were...
They signed their own names.
Yeah, that was the fall of 72.
Describe a football, home football game day, game day routine.
What time did things begin to happen?
I would several times had a date that would come in sometime that day.
You had the normal practice of buying the mums, you know, the big maroon and white mums.
You would go to lunch or breakfast, whichever was right, in the dining hall.
And then you'd have the march in and be in the stands and watch the game and parade around the campus after that and go eat and stay where you could and have a nice time and lose the ball game.
And marched in by, there was a full corps march in.
Just like there is today.
Because see, earlier that, you just went.
They followed the band, but they didn't, there was no... Oh, really?
No, we had the march-ins in my day.
The, let's see, and there normally was not a, if it was a day game, there normally was not a big organized Saturday night activity, was there?
Normally not, that I recall.
Right.
What about a court trip?
Describe that.
Court trips were interesting.
Of course, you got there by whatever arrangements you could make.
So you had four and five people in a car or whatever, usually staying at buddies' houses.
I had three guys where we stayed at an aunt and uncle's house my senior year in the Dallas area.
The Mother's Clubs did host Friday night dances in a major convention center, an easy place to get to.
And a lot of people would go to TWU and get dates and then come back for that dance and then carry them back to TWU.
And then Saturday morning, fairly early, 9 or 10 o'clock,
You would have the parade in the downtown of that city, and then the game in the afternoon.
Did you make most of the court trips?
Made them all, as far as I recall.
Was there a favorite and a least favorite of the four places?
I don't recall that being the case.
Do you remember any rudeness or meanness of the local folks in any of the four cities?
No.
Houston, Fort Worth, Dallas, and Austin.
There were probably more catcalls in Austin because you had a little broader, but I don't remember any.
I've heard stories about beast buckets and moose pots.
I've heard those stories.
Basically, some kind of bedding system that would relate to the quality of the dates, be they male or female.
Did you and your buddies write letters to TWU?
We did, to your PO box.
That's what I've heard.
The same number.
Did you ever do that?
I did it.
I don't remember anything coming out of it.
You don't remember a date?
I don't remember a connect.
Oh, okay.
But I remember doing it.
And they would come down here on the train?
Well, old days, but they would come on buses and cars in the 60s.
And stay everywhere?
Stay everywhere.
They would even clear out some dorm space, I think, and make room for them.
How were the girls treated?
I think very well.
I've never heard anything but positive that they kind of felt like they were royalty.
Yeah.
Were the big spring dances still going on?
Yes, they were.
Fish ball, sophomore ball, junior ball.
Cotton ball.
Boot dance, cotton ball.
Boot dance.
All happening.
Was there one that was notably bigger?
I think they were all fairly same size.
I mean, they were all pretty big.
They were mostly in Sebesa Dining Hall.
The combat bash was big, and you had a lot of extra people, a lot of military people, because it was on military weekend.
And it was usually in Duncan Dining Hall.
And then the military ball was more formal and was in Sebesa Dining Hall.
And in those days, they would have seven or eight general officers here as part of the festivities during that weekend, and they would all parade in and parade out.
And what was the behavior pattern for those?
Polite.
Straightforward.
Did you ever hitchhike?
I wasn't much on hitchhiking.
I did some.
And it was still happening when I first came back.
It probably stopped in the very early 70s is when it pretty much dried up.
But I would stop at the known spot in Houston when I was coming back.
Where was it?
From home.
It was on 290 on Hempstead Road.
I don't remember the exact location.
This side of what is now the 610 loop?
No, it would have been on the, oh, 610.
Yeah, it would have been out Hempstead out of 610.
Okay.
But not as far out as the new Beltway 8.
Yeah.
Did you ever hear of any negative?
Any Aggie that had a negative hitchhike experience?
I haven't.
I haven't yet heard of any.
And everyone emphasizes that there was, that rank did not matter when you were hitchhiking.
You took your turn.
Who was first.
Who was first.
And that in most of the big cities, there was a fairly known place that you went to, and you never held a sign up.
You just had on your uniform and your thumb.
Yeah, and they didn't all have uniforms on, you know, when I, in about 70, 69 and 70, when I was picking people up.
When you were an undergraduate, what were the most notable, and I'm using that word to mean most respected, student organizations?
If I wanted prestige, what organizations would I have tried to join?
Well, remember I had a very heavy Corps connection, so you would say the Ross Volunteers.
I think that the MSC Council had a very positive influence.
Student government by today's standards was teeny, but you still knew who some of those people were.
Corps Commander.
Yeah, if you named individuals, a core commander, student body president, head Yale leader.
Yale leaders were all known individuals, clearly a student leader.
Lots of leadership positions belong to the head Yale leader that have evolved into other things.
Bonfire orientation programs, muster, all of those are separate groups now.
Were you aware in that era of any secret fraternities?
I wasn't aware of any.
I've read everything about them in the last number of years, but it wasn't something that I knew about.
Let's see.
Brownfield had long ceased.
Right.
Let's see.
Did you have a car?
I didn't have a car.
Never had a car.
How'd you get around?
Friends.
Rode the bus.
How often would you go to and from Houston?
Two or three times a semester.
And just for the weekend.
Usually the weekend.
You would go because of a court trip.
You would go because of football games with people.
You went by bus more often than train?
Never went by train.
The train was pretty much not operating at that stage.
And about two hours?
The 60s.
Yeah, it was a little over two hours.
It was cheap.
Did you as a student have any interaction with the local community?
Did you go to church or anything off campus?
Went to the A&M, you know, the College Station Baptist, First Baptist.
Particularly my freshman year was not, I'd been active through high school and elementary, but I wasn't very active.
Was religious emphasis week?
Still happening.
And what was it like for a student?
All I remember is all of the organizations that had an orientation in that way, you know, had exposure, and if you wanted to have a level of involvement, you could.
In the summer, you went to Camp...
I went to summer school.
Of course, one summer was part of being laid out.
At the end of my sophomore year, I stayed in summer school.
End of my junior year, I stayed in summer school.
And then my senior year is when I went to camp after I graduated.
So that A&M didn't play any important role in helping you get a summer job or post-graduate experiences or anything like that?
No, remember I was only intending to be commissioned.
All right, let's see.
We've talked about court trips and student and game day.
What was final review like, particularly for a senior?
I think final review was pretty solemn.
People had just been commissioned and graduation had taken place, lots of families.
It was in early June, so it was hotter than the blue blazes.
I mean, it was very hot.
You were already felt like you felt kind of removed.
You felt like it was over.
You were essentially ready to go.
It's time to move on and do something else.
But pretty teary eyed.
It didn't take very long to change.
The time between the first review and the second review I don't think was very long.
There was very little monkey business that took place.
You just kind of marched across and you became the reviewing party.
That got out of hand in the late 70s and through some of the 80s and it just became a circus.
And the Corps has really done a good job of cleaning that up here in the last five or six years where I think it has a serious resemblance to the way it was in the past.
It's very orderly and very emotional.
I think the emotion is higher
Much higher.
Held on the drill field.
It's still held on the drill field.
Only time it wasn't is there was about a three-year period where Simpson Drill Field was being major re-sodded.
And do you remember who some of the reviewing officers, were they important?
I don't remember when I was a student.
I don't remember any of them.
How did you feel when you put on those senior boots officially the first time?
Felt pretty good.
That pour down rain at the end of that, all during that final review, just absolute quagmire.
Big smiles.
Mother came to that.
Mother.
Reese was still here on the staff, but mother and grandma.
Okay.
All right, then commencement.
Describe it.
Commencement, it was a full miracle that I graduated, and so 37 members of my family came to graduation.
Mother made arrangements for the buffet at the Ramada Inn at, I think, $5 a head, and they all ended up on the,
side of G. Raleigh on the west side and there was a photo taken of the stage and of that side and my entire family is in the photo in the yearbook.
Grandma, aunts, uncles, cousins.
I was the first to graduate from a college.
Do you remember who the speaker was?
I have no idea.
Almost no one, and whenever I make a commencement speech, I always indicate that I'm aware no one has come to hear the speaker.
They've come to see a certain person walk across the stage.
That's the reason they're there.
But your name was called and pronounced correctly.
Right.
And your hand was shaken.
And how long did it take you to look into the tube?
I probably looked pretty fast.
I'm convinced that's one of the very, very, very quiet important traditions.
Yeah, but to still do it.
Yes.
With, you know, 4,000 some odd graduating here in three ceremonies, you know, in a week.
It's just, it's so wonderful, but it's very extraordinary.
And almost every other institution I know of in the country has long ago...
Given up on it.
Given up and, you know, I hereby, therefore, will mail it to you and so no one attends.
It's awesome.
Yes.
And I've, of course, the last seven years I've been on the stage and for all three ceremonies and it's amazing how fast they go.
And I'm, I don't make a pre-list.
I just try to be alert.
And so I,
I don't know how many people I shake hands with, but a pretty big number.
And you have the ability to do that.
And it's really cool.
It's really neat.
One of my favorite anecdotes involved the messages that some students put on their morgue.
Yeah, we're all looking for those.
All right, my favorite one was about 25 years ago.
One young lad put on his, hell froze over.
Yeah, I can relate to that one.
Your first silver taps, do you remember that?
I remember going as a freshman.
You had to completely, everything was turned off.
We were still small, so there was an attempt to turn everything off, not just in the central academic area.
And we could stay up and study when we went back, but you had to have a blanket tucked into the window where there wasn't the slightest chance
of light getting out the window.
Very orderly, very quiet, very impressive.
Did it seem meaningful to you?
Very meaningful.
It's never lost it.
Did you have the impression that it was just like it had been for many, many years?
Yes.
All right.
What about muster?
Did you go to muster?
Yes.
It was on the lawn of the MSC one year.
It was on the lawn of the administration building, like one near.
I have good memories.
I don't remember them being too terribly long.
I don't remember any speakers.
But the ceremony and the impact of the firing squad and the roll call and everything is a very strong memory.
As you were getting ready to leave the campus as a graduating senior, how well prepared did you feel A&M had made you?
I felt fine and fully prepared to be an army officer and thought that I would do okay and did okay.
If you could today line up all of the people that you now know had a positive effect on your career from those undergraduate days, who would you most want to?
Well, I've named most of them already.
It wasn't a huge list, but mother has an impact, grandma has an impact,
The ants sending brownies when you're a fish has an impact.
Aunt Ruth's brownies were the best brownies in the world.
And when you show up with a shoebox, there's a real clue what this is.
And so all of a sudden, you were a really nice guy.
Calvin Reese played a very important point.
Dan Lowe played an important point.
George Rice.
There were people that stepped up when they were given the opportunity.
Hannigan was very nice every time I had anything to do with him, very supportive.
He knew that I was just as mediocre a student as I was.
